62–Male":"1362–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1305–1344":"1305–1344","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","Abt 1357":"about 1357","November 1387":"November 1387","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1356":"1356","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1387":"1387","about 1330":"about 1330","about 1362":"about 1362","1438":"1438","Wales":"Wales","Wernddu, Monmouthshire, England":"England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Herbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, English, and French: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. In Britain, this Old French name, introduced by the Normans, reinforced the less common Old English cognate <i>Herebeorht</i>. The surname was taken to Ireland after the Anglo-Norman invasion and in the 16th century.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the German personal name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Harbison","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert   (the change from <i>-er-</i> to <i>-ar-</i> was a common one in Old French and Middle English). An intrusive <i>n</i> later gave   Harbinson  ."]},{"name":"Hebard","meanings":["English (Surrey):","variant of   Herbert  , with assimilation of the first <i>r</i>. Compare   Hebb  .","variant of   Hibbert  ."]},{"name":"Harbert","meanings":["German and English: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbers","meanings":["German and Dutch: patronymic from   Herbert  . It is found mainly in Lower Saxony and across the Dutch border."]},{"name":"Dickherber","meanings":["Probably a nickname for a fat person by the name of   Herbert  , of which <i>Herber</i> is a short form, or, more likely, in the north from <b>Die(c)kherber</b>, a topographic and distinguishing name for a <i>Herber</i> living by the dike, see   Dicke   2. Compare   Dickmeyer  ."]},{"name":"Hebert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Emile, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Pierre, Lucien, Michel, Gaston, Alcide, Camille.","French (<b>Hébert</b>): assimilated form of   Herbert  . Compare   Abair  ,   Abar  ,   Abare  ,   Abear  ,   Aber  ,   Eber  , and   Ebert  .","German: variant of   Heber   1."]},{"name":"Herber","meanings":["German and Dutch: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbertson","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Hebb","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire and northeast Midlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hebb</i>, <i>Ebb</i>, pet forms of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herb","meanings":["South German: nickname for a harsh or rough person, from Middle High German <i>herb</i> ‘tart, harsh’.","German: from the personal name <i>Herpo</i>, a pet form of   Herbert  ."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jenkin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is derived from the medieval given name <i>Jankin</i>. This was a pet form of the boy's name   Jan  , with the diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. The modern given name is popular in Wales, where the surnames <i>Jenkin</i> and <i>Jenkins</i> are common."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Philip Ap Jenkin Herbert was born about 1330, in Wales as the son of Jenkin ap Adam lord Wernddu. He married Alicia about 1357, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in November 1387, in Canterbury, Kent, England, at the age of 58."},"et":{"about 1330–November 1387":"umbes 1330–november 1387","1330–1387":"1330–1387","1327–Female":"1327–Surnud","1356–1438":"1356–1438","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1305–1344":"1305–1344","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","Abt 1357":"umbes 1357","November 1387":"november 1387","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1356":"1356","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1387":"1387","about 1330":"umbes 1330","about 1362":"umbes 1362","1438":"1438","Wales":"Wales","Wernddu, Monmouthshire, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1330–November 1387":"noin 1330–marraskuu 1387","1330–1387":"1330–1387","1327–Female":"1327–Kuollut","1356–1438"